comments.body:
@AndersMad I have not tried this, but I think this is the way to control it: 

```
SKPaint paint = ...;
paint.FilterQuality = SKFilterQuality.High;
```

> Gets or sets the filter quality of the current paint.
> This affects the quality (and performance) of drawing scaled images.
> https://developer.xamarin.com/api/property/SkiaSharp.SKPaint.FilterQuality/

Let me know what happens - and you can try the other values and see if that is faster/better.
